column1: As of 28 December 2017, how many cholera deaths will the Humanitarian Data Exchange record in Yemen?
column5: ['Less than 2,300', 'Between 2,300 and 2,500, inclusive', 'More than 2,500 but less than 3,000 ', '3,000 or more']
column6: ['Health', 'Environment']
column11: The WHO has reported that a cholera outbreak in Yemen has surged since the end of April (Reuters, Financial Times, CNN, The Guardian). Outcome will be determined by data from the Humanitarian Data Exchange (HDX), which provides a cumulative count of Yemen's cholera deaths since 27 April 2017, using WHO data. The relevant data can be found by downloading the "Yemen Cholera Outbreak Epidemiology Data," looking at the most recent entry in the "Deaths" column of the "Data_Country_Level" tab. If HDX stops tracking cholera cases in Yemen, the question will resolve based on the final available HDX numbers. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

We're 81 potential deaths away from 2300; the last 81 deaths began to occur in early October, so the death rate per time would need to nearly double between the last measurement and the end of the year. Blockade was late November; unclear if its effects are in in the most recently published (late November) data. Even if they aren't (& indeed possibly there were no such effects), doubling the rate would be a substantial increase. So I remain skewed toward the 2,300 bucket. I still think it's possible the number jumps significantly enough to pass 2300 in December, but I think more than 2500 is remote.

Crunching the numbers. Point Case Fatality Rate (as opposed to cumulative CFR) has been essentially bi-modal. Before July, during the acceleration phase of the outbreak, the CFR was generally at or above 0.5% (1 in 200 cases died). Since mid-August, the CFR has generally been at or below 0.05% (1 in 2000 cases die). July and early August was a transition period between the two.
